ome together despite the experiences that set them apart? The book will be useful to those studying Jewish, American, or New York history, the Holocaust and Catskills legacy, United States immigration, American literature, and American culture. The focus on themes of nostalgia, humor, loss, and sexuality will draw general readers as well.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aHolocaust survivorszNew York (State)zCatskill Mountains. 0aHolocaust survivors' writings. 70(DE-601)10430670X0(DE-588)4028808-0aJuden2gnd 70(DE-601)1046751520(DE-588)4049716-1aRezeption2gnd 70(DE-601)1046825900(DE-588)4073091-8aJudenvernichtung2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-588)4035964-5aLiteratur2gnd 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Phil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertASP eBook Package Backlist 2008-2015z978311068814640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618114198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618114198.jpg  a978-3-11-068814-6  ASP eBook Package Backlist 2008-2015c2008d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG